  "proof_sketch": "The mutation changes `sqrtf(sdata[0] + 1e-8f)` to `sqrtf(sdata[0] - 1e-8f)`. When the squared sum `sdata[0]` is less than 1e-8, the mutant computes sqrt of a negative number, producing NaN. Original always produces a finite value. With fixed shape [16,16384] and float32, a zero-valued input yields `sdata[0]=0`, making the mutant produce NaN while original outputs zeros. All previous tests (large magnitude, mixed extremes) had sums much larger than 1e-8, so the subtraction was negligible and results were bitwise identical.",
  "survival_reason": "The mutation survived because the test suite never exercised inputs with near-zero L2 norms. All tested value distributions (large magnitudes ~1e6, mixed extremes of 1e6 and 1e-6) produced squared sums far exceeding 1e-8, so the change from + to - was numerically imperceptible (floating-point addition/subtraction of 1e-8 was lost in rounding). A zero or extremely small input vector would cause the mutated kernel to compute `sqrt(negative) = NaN`, which is easily detected by bitwise comparison.",
  "killable": true,
  "kill_strategy": "Use an input tensor of all zeros (or very small values such that the sum of squares is less than 1e-8). The original kernel will produce a normalized output (all zeros), while the mutated kernel will produce NaN. This yields a clear bitwise mismatch.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "Zero-valued input to force L2 norm sum to zero, triggering NaN in the mutated kernel.",
    "python_code": "def generate_inputs(device):\n    return [torch.zeros((16, 16384), dtype=torch.float32, device=device)]"
  },
  "recommendations": "Add test cases with zero or near-zero input vectors to verify numerical stability of normalization kernels, especially when epsilon is subtracted instead of added."
